# Linux Fundamentals

## Commands I learned
- whoami → shows current user
- ls → lists files
- pwd → shows current directory

## What I did
Used `whoami` to confirm I was logged in as a normal user.

whoami      # current user
id          # user + group info
hostname    # machine name
uname -a    # system info

pwd         # where am I
ls          # list files
ls -la      # show hidden + details
cd folder   # move into folder
cd ..       # go back

cat file.txt        # read file
less file.txt       # scroll file
head file.txt       # first lines
tail file.txt       # last lines
cp file1 file2      # copy
mv file1 file2      # move/rename
rm file.txt         # delete

find / -name file.txt 2>/dev/null
grep "word" file.txt

ls -l
chmod +x file.sh
chmod 777 file.txt

## What I Look For First
- Current user (whoami)
- Sudo permissions (sudo -l)
- SUID files
- Interesting files (ls -la)
- System info (uname -a)

## Common Strategy
1. Enumerate everything
2. Look for misconfigurations
3. Try privilege escalation
